   <mods:abstract>Hamilton has been appointed Inspector General with the rank of Major
            General; worries about the effect since he was not "taken from the line." Enjoys reading
            John Jay's sentiments and shows how they coincide with his own by enclosing a copy of
            his letter to Washington of the 6th [NNC: 9507]. The Senate has voted the President's
            nomination of his son-in-law, William S. Smith, to adjutant general with the rank of
            brigadier. The President was unaware that Smith "was a bankrupt in fame as well as
            fortune." Pickering therefore hopes his own interference in the appointment will not be
            ill-judged.</mods:abstract>
